answer.en:
### Fiber Architecture

Fiber is React's reconciliation unit—each component instance is a fiber with references to parent, child, and sibling fibers. Fibers are work units that can be paused, prioritized, and resumed, enabling concurrent rendering.

Traditional stack reconcilers complete entire tree rendering before yielding control. Fibers break this into chunks: React renders incrementally, yields to browser events, and can abandon low-priority work if high-priority updates arrive. Each fiber tracks pendingProps, memoizedProps, hooks state, and lane information.

typescript
// Conceptual Fiber structure
interface Fiber {
  type: any;
  key: string | null;
  ref: any;
  props: any;
  child: Fiber | null;
  sibling: Fiber | null;
  return: Fiber | null; // Parent
  pendingProps: any;
  memoizedProps: any;
  hooks: Hook[] | null;
  lane: Lane;
  alternate: Fiber | null; // Work-in-progress
}

// React can pause here and resume later
function scheduleWork(fiber: Fiber, lane: Lane) {
  if (!fiber.lane) fiber.lane = lane;
  else fiber.lane = mergeLanes(fiber.lane, lane);
}


**Common interview trap:** Candidates confuse fibers with components—fibers are internal runtime structures, multiple fibers can exist per component.

answer.ru:
### Архитектура Fiber

Fiber—единица reconciliation в React—каждый экземпляр компонента это fiber со ссылками на parent, child, sibling. Fibers могут быть paused, приоритизированы, resumed, позволяя concurrent rendering.

Традиционные reconciler завершают весь рендер до yield. Fibers разбивают на chunks: React рендерит инкрементально, может отказаться от низкого приоритета.

typescript
// Концептуальная структура Fiber
interface Fiber {
  type: any;
  key: string | null;
  ref: any;
  props: any;
  child: Fiber | null;
  sibling: Fiber | null;
  return: Fiber | null; // Parent
  pendingProps: any;
  memoizedProps: any;
  hooks: Hook[] | null;
  lane: Lane;
  alternate: Fiber | null; // Work-in-progress
}

function scheduleWork(fiber: Fiber, lane: Lane) {
  if (!fiber.lane) fiber.lane = lane;
  else fiber.lane = mergeLanes(fiber.lane, lane);
}


**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Путают fiber с компонентом—fiber это внутренняя структура рантайма.

answer.en:
### Controlled vs Uncontrolled

Controlled components: React state drives the input value. Every keystroke updates state, triggering re-render. Uncontrolled: the DOM maintains state via refs, React doesn't track value changes.

Controlled pros: predictable, easy validation, dynamic disabling. Cons: every change re-renders, more boilerplate. Uncontrolled pros: simpler code, single-line inputs. Cons: can't easily validate, harder to integrate.

Use controlled for complex forms, validation, dynamic behavior. Use uncontrolled for simple inputs, file uploads, or integration with non-React libraries.

typescript
// Controlled
function Controlled() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');
  return <input value={value} onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)} />;
}

// Uncontrolled
function Uncontrolled() {
  const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);
  const handleSubmit = () => console.log(inputRef.current?.value);
  return (
    <>
      <input ref={inputRef} />
      <button onClick={handleSubmit}>Get value</button>
    </>
  );
}


**Common interview trap:** Candidates think uncontrolled means no React state—uncontrolled still needs React state for form-level logic, just not per-field.

answer.ru:
### Управляемые vs неуправляемые

Управляемые: React state управляет значением input. Каждый keystroke обновляет state. Неуправляемые: DOM хранит state через ref.

Управляемые плюсы: предсказуемо, легко валидировать, динамический disable. Минусы: каждое изменение—re-render. Неуправляемые плюсы: проще код. Минусы: сложнее валидировать.

Используйте управляемые для сложных форм, валидации. Неуправляемые для простых input, file upload.

typescript
// Управляемый
function Controlled() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');
  return <input value={value} onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)} />;
}

// Неуправляемый
function Uncontrolled() {
  const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);
  const handleSubmit = () => console.log(inputRef.current?.value);
  return (
    <>
      <input ref={inputRef} />
      <button onClick={handleSubmit}>Get value</button>
    </>
  );
}


**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Думают, неуправляемые не нужны React state—ошибка, нужен для уровня формы.

answer.en:
### Error Boundaries

Error Boundaries are class components that catch JavaScript errors in child components during rendering, lifecycle, and constructors. They prevent the entire app from crashing by displaying fallback UI.

Difference from try-catch: try-catch catches errors in event handlers and async code; Error Boundaries catch rendering errors. They're complementary—use Error Boundaries for component tree crashes, try-catch for async operations and event handlers. Error Boundaries don't catch errors in themselves, effects, or event handlers.

typescript
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = { hasError: false, error: null };

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    return { hasError: true, error };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error, errorInfo) {
    console.log('Error caught:', error, errorInfo);
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      return <div>Something went wrong: {this.state.error.message}</div>;
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}

// Usage
<ErrorBoundary>
  <ProblematicComponent />
</ErrorBoundary>


**Common interview trap:** Candidates think Error Boundaries work with hooks or functional components—they only work in class components.

answer.ru:
### Error Boundaries

Error Boundaries—class компоненты, ловящие ошибки в child компонентах во время рендера, lifecycle, конструктора. Предотвращают крах приложения.

Отличие от try-catch: try-catch ловит ошибки в event handler и async; Error Boundaries—во время рендера. Дополняют друг друга. Error Boundaries не ловят ошибки в себе, effects, event handler.

typescript
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = { hasError: false, error: null };

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    return { hasError: true, error };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error, errorInfo) {
    console.log('Error caught:', error, errorInfo);
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      return <div>Something went wrong: {this.state.error.message}</div>;
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}

<ErrorBoundary>
  <ProblematicComponent />
</ErrorBoundary>


**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Думают, что Error Boundaries работают с hooks—только class компоненты.

answer.en:
### Large List Optimization

Windowing (virtualization) renders only visible items plus a buffer, dramatically reducing DOM nodes and improving performance. Combine with React.memo to prevent unnecessary child re-renders, and memoize list item components.

Critical: use stable, unique keys—never index-based keys as they cause incorrect reconciliation when lists change. Consider libraries like react-window or react-virtualized for proven implementations.

typescript
import { FixedSizeList } from 'react-window';
import { memo } from 'react';

const Row = memo(({ index, style, data }) => (
  <div style={style}>{data[index].name}</div>
));

function VirtualList({ items }) {
  return (
    <FixedSizeList
      height={600}
      itemCount={items.length}
      itemSize={35}
      width="100%"
      itemData={items}
    >
      {Row}
    </FixedSizeList>
  );
}


**Common interview trap:** Candidates suggest filtering/searching as optimization—it helps but doesn't solve rendering 10k items. Windowing is essential.

answer.ru:
### Оптимизация большого списка

Windowing (виртуализация) рендерит только видимые элементы + буфер, снижает DOM nodes. Объедините с React.memo для предотвращения re-render child компонентов.

Критично: стабильные, уникальные key—никогда не index-based key. Рассмотрите react-window для готовой реализации.

typescript
import { FixedSizeList } from 'react-window';
import { memo } from 'react';

const Row = memo(({ index, style, data }) => (
  <div style={style}>{data[index].name}</div>
));

function VirtualList({ items }) {
  return (
    <FixedSizeList
      height={600}
      itemCount={items.length}
      itemSize={35}
      width="100%"
      itemData={items}
    >
      {Row}
    </FixedSizeList>
  );
}


**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Предлагают фильтр/поиск как оптимизацию—это помогает, но не решает проблему 10k. Windowing критично.

answer.en:
### TypeScript with React

Benefits: type safety for props/state, excellent IDE support, refactoring safety, self-documenting code. Challenges: increased boilerplate, longer development time initially, steep learning curve for generics.

For complex patterns, use generics for reusable components: Higher-Order Components, render props, hooks that accept type parameters. Define prop interfaces separately, use React.FC<Props> or function return type annotations.

typescript
interface WithDataProps<T> {
  data: T[];
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
}

function withData<T>(Component: React.ComponentType<WithDataProps<T>>) {
  return function DataComponent(props: Omit<WithDataProps<T>, 'data'>) {
    const [data, setData] = useState<T[]>([]);
    return <Component {...props} data={data} />;
  };
}

type UseAsync<T> = {
  data: T | null;
  loading: boolean;
  error: Error | null;
};

function useAsync<T>(fn: () => Promise<T>): UseAsync<T> {
  const [state, setState] = useState<UseAsync<T>>({
    data: null,
    loading: true,
    error: null
  });
  // ...
  return state;
}


**Common interview trap:** Candidates over-use `any`—it defeats TypeScript. Use generics and proper type inference instead.

answer.ru:
### TypeScript с React

Преимущества: type safety для props/state, IDE support, безопасность рефакторинга. Сложности: boilerplate, долгая разработка, learning curve для generics.

Для сложных паттернов используйте generics: HOC, render props, hooks с type параметрами. Отделите prop interface, используйте React.FC<Props>.

typescript
interface WithDataProps<T> {
  data: T[];
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
}

function withData<T>(Component: React.ComponentType<WithDataProps<T>>) {
  return function DataComponent(props: Omit<WithDataProps<T>, 'data'>) {
    const [data, setData] = useState<T[]>([]);
    return <Component {...props} data={data} />;
  };
}

type UseAsync<T> = {
  data: T | null;
  loading: boolean;
  error: Error | null;
};

function useAsync<T>(fn: () => Promise<T>): UseAsync<T> {
