  return state;
}


**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Используют `any`—это поражение TypeScript. Используйте generics.

answer.en:
### Lazy Loading & Code Splitting

Code splitting breaks bundle into chunks loaded on demand. Lazy loading defers component/resource loading until needed. Combined, they reduce initial bundle size and improve First Contentful Paint.

React.lazy enables dynamic imports: only chunks for visible routes/components load initially. Suspense manages loading states. Webpack and other bundlers detect dynamic imports and create separate chunks automatically.

typescript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';

const Home = lazy(() => import('./pages/Home'));
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));

function App() {
  const [page, setPage] = useState('home');

  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
      {page === 'home' ? <Home /> : <Dashboard />}
    </Suspense>
  );
}

// Route-based splitting with React Router
const routes = [
  { path: '/', element: lazy(() => import('./Home')) },
  { path: '/about', element: lazy(() => import('./About')) }
];


**Common interview trap:** Candidates think code splitting requires manual configuration—bundlers detect dynamic import() automatically.

answer.ru:
### Lazy Loading и Code Splitting

Code splitting разбивает бандл на chunks, загружаемые по требованию. Lazy loading откладывает загрузку компонента. Вместе: уменьшают initial bundle, улучшают FCP.

React.lazy включает динамический import: только chunks видимых route/компонент загружаются. Suspense управляет loading state. Webpack автоматически создаёт chunks.

typescript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';

const Home = lazy(() => import('./pages/Home'));
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));

function App() {
  const [page, setPage] = useState('home');

  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
      {page === 'home' ? <Home /> : <Dashboard />}
    </Suspense>
  );
}

const routes = [
  { path: '/', element: lazy(() => import('./Home')) },
  { path: '/about', element: lazy(() => import('./About')) }
];


**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Думают, что code splitting нужна ручная конфигурация—bundler это автоматически.

answer.en:
### State Management Comparison

Context: built-in, good for simple global state (themes, auth), but causes unnecessary re-renders when unrelated state changes. Redux: centralized, predictable, DevTools, but boilerplate-heavy. Zustand: minimal, hook-based, no boilerplate, but smaller ecosystem.

Context for: theme, language, auth. Redux for: large apps with complex async flows, time-travel debugging needs. Zustand for: modern, small-to-medium apps wanting simplicity without Redux ceremony.

typescript
// Zustand (recommended for modern apps)
import { create } from 'zustand';

const useStore = create((set) => ({
  user: null,
  setUser: (user) => set({ user }),
  logout: () => set({ user: null })
}));

// Use in components
function Profile() {
  const { user, logout } = useStore();
  return <button onClick={logout}>{user?.name}</button>;
}

// Context (simple use case)
const ThemeContext = createContext('light');
export function ThemeProvider({ children }) {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');
  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>
      {children}
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}


**Common interview trap:** Candidates over-engineer with Redux for simple apps or use Context when they need selector memoization—understand trade-offs.

answer.ru:
